{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507586"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:54:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:54:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2645"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2645"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.07,0.76,0.07,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2645"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66549"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2645"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2645"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52002"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1546"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"7982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3048"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3054"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18301"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42535"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66549","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66549"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-week history of a burning red rash on her lower legs. The rash worsens at the end of the day after being at work. Several weeks ago, she had a sore throat and headache for which she took ibuprofen. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are palpable petechiae and purpura across the bilateral dorsum of feet, ankles and distal shins. Below her right lateral malleolus, there is an ulcer in the centre of coalesced purpuric lesions. The rash is non-blanching. There are no other skin findings elsewhere.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA skin biopsy reveals perivascular neutrophilic infiltrate with leukocytoclasis and fibrinoid necrosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following symptoms is characteristic of systemic involvement?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Polydipsia","Lip swelling","Haematuria","Hyperhidrosis","Alopecia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of leukocytoclastic vasculitis (hypersensitivity vasculitis), a small vessel vasculitis characterised by palpable purpura in dependent areas. The history of preceding upper respiratory tract infection and ibuprofen use suggests possible triggers, though the cause is often unknown.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGeneral signs of systemic vasculitis can include fever, headache, fatigue, weight loss, myalgia and arthralgia. Other organ-specific features can include abdominal pain, gastric ulcers, haematochezia, tinnitus, vertigo, abrupt hearing loss, eye pain, vision loss, peripheral neuropathy, shortness of breath, haemoptysis, and haematuria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaematuria\u003C/strong\u003E is a critical sign of systemic involvement in vasculitis, particularly indicating renal involvement. This finding would warrant urgent investigation including renal function tests, urinalysis, and possible renal biopsy as it may indicate a more serious condition such as ANCA-associated vasculitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolydipsia\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically associated with systemic vasculitis. While patients may experience constitutional symptoms, increased thirst is not a characteristic feature of systemic involvement.  It is more often associated with new-onset of diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELip swelling\u003C/strong\u003E may occur in angioedema or allergic reactions as a type 1 hypersensitivity reaction, but is not a typical feature of systemic vasculitis. While some patients may develop oral ulcers, isolated lip swelling would not suggest systemic disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperhidrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is not a recognised feature of systemic vasculitis. Systemic symptoms typically include fever, fatigue, weight loss, myalgia, and arthralgia, but not increased sweating.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlopecia\u003C/strong\u003E is not characteristic of systemic vasculitis. While it may occur in autoimmune conditions that can be associated with vasculitis (such as systemic lupus erythematosus), it is not a primary feature indicating systemic involvement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cutaneous small vessel vasculitis commonly presents with palpable purpura on dependent areas, particularly the lower legs.","Haematuria is a key indicator of systemic involvement in vasculitis requiring urgent investigation.","Skin biopsy showing leukocytoclastic vasculitis is diagnostic but does not differentiate between systemic and cutaneous-limited disease."],"references":["Alberti-Violetti S, Berti E, Marzano AV. Cutaneous and systemic vasculitides in dermatology: a histological perspective. G Ital Dermatol Venereol. 2018 Apr;153(2):185-193. doi: 10.23736/S0392-0488.18.05886-8. Epub 2018 Jan 24. PMID: 29368866.","Sharma P, Sharma S, Baltaro R, Hurley J. Systemic vasculitis. Am Fam Physician. 2011 Mar 1;83(5):556-65. PMID: 21391523.","Mahoney SL, Nachman PN. Persistent Hematuria in ANCA Vasculitis. Clin J AM Soc Nephrol 2018: 13: 201\u201302."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52002"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2645"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52002","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52002"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-30T23:19:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-30T23:19:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2645"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66549"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"upda